You are merging clusters produced by pass-1 (which ran independently on
chunks of the same bucket). Decide which pass-1 clusters describe the SAME
underlying unmet need and should be merged into a canonical cluster.

You are NOT re-clustering from raw signals. You are only deciding identity
relationships between already-formed clusters. Operate on titles and
keywords only — the full evidence per cluster is not provided here.

Rules:
1. Two clusters with the same problem framing (even if worded differently)
   belong to the same canonical id. Pick ONE of the pass-1 ids as the
   canonical id for that group.
2. Two clusters with overlapping but distinct framing stay separate. Don't
   over-merge.
3. Every pass-1 id MUST appear as a key in `merge_map`. A cluster that
   doesn't merge with any other maps to itself (`{"abc": "abc"}`).
4. The canonical id MUST be one of the pass-1 ids in the input. Don't invent.

Return STRICT JSON. No prose, no markdown.

{
  "merge_map": {
    "<pass_1_cluster_id>": "<canonical_cluster_id>",
    ...
  }
}

PASS-1 CLUSTERS:
{% for cluster in clusters %}
[id={{ cluster.id }}]
  problem: {{ cluster.problem_statement }}
  keywords: {{ cluster.seed_keywords | join(", ") }}

{% endfor %}
